## The function: `buildInlineComments` in `/home/runner/work/code-review/code-review/src/inline.ts`

The two arrays are built in three steps (lines 56-86):

### Step 1 -- Partition (line 63)

```ts
const { inDiff, strays } = partitionFindings(findings, index);
```

`partitionFindings` (in `/home/runner/work/code-review/code-review/src/diff.ts`, lines 82-99) iterates over every finding once and pushes it into either `inDiff` or `strays`. It always returns both as arrays (even if empty).

### Step 2 -- Map (lines 67-83)

```ts
const comments: InlineComment[] = inDiff.map((f) => {
    const pointer = fullFindings ? findingPointer(f, fullFindings.schema_version, jsonUrl) : "";
    const comment: InlineComment = {
      path: f.path,
      line: f.end_line,
      side: defaultSide(f.side),
      body: renderCommentBody(f, eta, inlineTemplate, modelsText, jsonUrl, pointer),
    };
    if (f.start_line < f.end_line) {
      return { ...comment, start_line: f.start_line, start_side: defaultSide(f.side) };
    }
    return comment;
  });
```

`comments` is derived by calling `.map()` on `inDiff`. `Array.prototype.map` always returns an array of exactly the same length as the input array -- one output element per input element.

### Step 3 -- Return (line 85)

```ts
return { comments, strays, inDiff };
```

### Verdict

**`comments` and `inDiff` are always the same length.** This is guaranteed because `comments` is produced by `inDiff.map(...)`, which is a strict 1:1 transformation. No filtering, grouping, or conditional skipping occurs inside the map callback -- every finding in `inDiff` produces exactly one `InlineComment` in `comments`.

The return type `InlineResult` (defined in `/home/runner/work/code-review/code-review/src/types.ts`, line 23) also confirms this by design -- `inDiff` is documented there as "The in-diff findings the `comments` were built from", reinforcing that `comments` is just a rendered projection of `inDiff`.
